#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:1
msgid "The DeviceOperation Model"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:3
msgid ""
"In the [Writing GPU Programs](../gpu-programming/launching-kernels.md) "
"chapter, you saw that typed sync launches enqueue work on an explicit "
"stream, while typed async launches return a lazy handle that defers stream "
"selection. This chapter digs into the abstraction behind that lazy handle -- "
"the **`DeviceOperation`** trait -- and explains why decoupling *what* the "
"GPU should do from *which stream* it runs on is the foundation of composable "
"async GPU programming in cuda-oxide."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:12
msgid ""
"[CUDA Programming Guide -- Asynchronous Concurrent Execution](https://docs."
"nvidia.com/cuda/cuda-programming-guide/#asynchronous-concurrent-execution) "
"for the underlying CUDA stream and event model that `DeviceOperation` builds "
"on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:16
msgid "Why lazy operations?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:18
msgid ""
"In CUDA C++, you build concurrency by creating multiple `cudaStream_t` "
"handles and placing kernel launches and memory copies onto them explicitly. "
"The programmer decides at every call site which stream to use. This couples "
"the *definition* of GPU work to the *scheduling decision*, making it hard to "
"compose and rearrange work after the fact."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:24
msgid ""
"cuda-oxide takes a different approach. A `DeviceOperation` describes GPU "
"work without binding to any stream. You can compose operations with "
"combinators (`and_then`, `zip!`), pass them across function boundaries, "
"store them in collections, and only decide how to schedule them at the last "
"moment. This is the same idea behind Rust's `Iterator` -- build the pipeline "
"lazily, execute it eagerly at the call site."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:11
msgid "Approach"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:11
msgid "Stream chosen by"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:11
msgid "Composable?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:11
msgid "Typed sync launch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:11
msgid "Caller"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:11
msgid "No, enqueued immediately"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:11
msgid "Typed async launch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:11
msgid "Scheduling policy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:11
msgid "Yes, returns `DeviceOperation`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:40
msgid ""
"The DeviceOperation lifecycle. Phase 1: a typed async method builds a lazy "
"recipe (no GPU work). Phase 2: the scheduling policy picks a stream from its "
"pool. Phase 3: `execute()` submits GPU work and a `cuLaunchHostFunc` "
"callback. Phase 4: the callback fires, wakes the async runtime, and delivers "
"the result. Bottom: the four execution methods from simplest (`.sync()`) to "
"most manual (`async_on`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:48
msgid "Recipes and kitchens"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:50
msgid ""
"Think of a `DeviceOperation` as a **recipe card**. The card describes every "
"step of the dish -- what ingredients to combine, at what temperature, for "
"how long -- but it does not say *which kitchen* will cook it. You can hand "
"the card to any kitchen, photocopy it, staple two cards together into a "
"multi-course meal, or file it away for later. The dish only starts cooking "
"when someone walks into a kitchen and begins following the instructions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:57
msgid "In cuda-oxide's model:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:59
msgid "A **recipe** is a `DeviceOperation` -- a lazy description of GPU work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:60
msgid ""
"A **kitchen** is a CUDA stream -- the in-order queue where work actually "
"runs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:61
msgid ""
"The **head chef** is a `SchedulingPolicy` -- the logic that decides which "
"kitchen handles each recipe."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:63
msgid ""
"The **meal** is the `Output` -- the result you get when everything is done."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:65
msgid ""
"This separation is what makes the system composable. You can write a "
"function that returns a recipe for \"upload data, run GEMM, apply ReLU\" "
"without caring which stream will execute it. The caller can chain more steps "
"onto the recipe, run it on a specific stream, or hand it to the scheduling "
"policy and walk away."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:70
msgid "Your first async launch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:72
msgid ""
"The simplest way to create a `DeviceOperation` is a generated `{kernel}"
"_async` method. It looks like the sync method, but without the stream "
"argument, and it returns a recipe instead of cooking immediately:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:76
msgid ""
"use cuda_async::device_context::init_device_contexts;\n"
"use cuda_core::LaunchConfig;\n"
"\n"
"// One-time setup: create a stream pool for scheduling\n"
"init_device_contexts(0, 1)?;\n"
"\n"
"// Build the recipe (no GPU work yet)\n"
"let module = kernels::load_async(0)?;\n"
"// SAFETY: this is 1D, buffers contain 1024 elements, and module/scheduler\n"
"// both use device 0's context.\n"
"let op = unsafe {\n"
"    module.vecadd_async(\n"
"        LaunchConfig::for_num_elems(1024),\n"
"        &a_dev,\n"
"        &b_dev,\n"
"        &mut c_dev,\n"
"    )\n"
"}?;\n"
"\n"
"// Now cook it: pick a stream, launch, wait for the result\n"
"op.sync()?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:100
msgid ""
"At the point where `op` is created, nothing has happened on the GPU. The "
"method builds an `AsyncKernelLaunch` value that remembers which function to "
"call, what arguments to pass, and how to configure the grid -- but it does "
"not touch any stream. It is a recipe card sitting on the counter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:105
msgid ""
"The `unsafe` is about accepting an unproved raw `LaunchConfig`, not about "
"building lazily. A contracted kernel uses a checked `PreparedLaunch<K>` and "
"a safe generated async method:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:109
msgid ""
"raw config -> unsafe async recipe\n"
"prepared K -> safe async recipe for K\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:114
msgid ""
"When you call `.sync()`, the scheduling policy picks a stream from its pool, "
"submits the kernel, and blocks until the stream is idle. That single line is "
"where the recipe becomes a cooked meal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:118
msgid "What makes a `DeviceOperation`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:120
msgid ""
"Behind the scenes, `DeviceOperation` is a trait. Any type that describes GPU "
"work can implement it. The trait has one required method and one associated "
"type:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:123
msgid ""
"pub trait DeviceOperation: Send + Sized + IntoFuture {\n"
"    type Output: Send;\n"
"\n"
"    unsafe fn execute(\n"
"        self,\n"
"        context: &ExecutionContext,\n"
"    ) -> Result<Self::Output, DeviceError>;\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:134
msgid ""
"**`Output`** is the Rust value the operation produces when it finishes. For "
"a kernel launch this is `()` -- the kernel runs for its side effects on "
"device memory. For a device-to-host copy it might be `Vec<f32>`. For a "
"memory allocation it could be a `DeviceBox<[f32]>` that owns the pointer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:139
msgid ""
"**`execute`** is where the actual GPU work happens. It receives an "
"`ExecutionContext` -- the assigned kitchen -- and submits work to the stream "
"inside it. The method is `unsafe` because GPU work may still be in flight "
"when it returns; the caller is responsible for synchronizing before reading "
"results."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:144
msgid ""
"The `Send` bound means operations can move across threads (essential for "
"`tokio::spawn`). The `IntoFuture` bound is what makes `.await` work -- more "
"on that shortly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:148
msgid ""
"You rarely implement `DeviceOperation` yourself. The crate provides a set of "
"types that implement it, and you compose them using combinators:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:151
msgid ""
"**`AsyncKernelLaunch`** -- produced by typed async launch methods. Launches "
"a kernel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:152
msgid ""
"**`Value<T>`** -- wraps a host-side value. No GPU work. Returns `T` "
"immediately."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:153
msgid "**`AndThen`** -- chains two operations: run A, feed the result to B."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:154
msgid "**`Zip`** -- runs two operations and returns both results as a tuple."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:155
msgid "**`StreamOperation`** -- defers construction until the stream is known."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:157
msgid ""
"These are the building blocks of every async pipeline. The [Combinators and "
"Composition](combinators-and-composition.md) chapter covers each one in "
"detail."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:161
msgid "The `ExecutionContext` -- where the stream lives"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:163
msgid ""
"When a recipe is executed, it needs to know which kitchen it is in. The "
"`ExecutionContext` carries that information:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:166
msgid ""
"pub struct ExecutionContext {\n"
"    device: usize,              // which GPU\n"
"    cuda_stream: Arc<CudaStream>,   // which stream\n"
"    cuda_context: Arc<CudaContext>, // which CUDA context\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:174
msgid ""
"Operations never create streams themselves. The scheduling policy (covered "
"in [Scheduling and Streams](scheduling-and-streams.md)) creates the "
"`ExecutionContext` and passes it into `execute`. This is the core of the "
"separation: operations describe *what*, the context provides *where*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:179
msgid ""
"Inside an `execute` implementation, you access the stream with `ctx."
"get_cuda_stream()` and the CUDA context with `ctx.get_cuda_context()`. For "
"most operations this is all you need -- enqueue a kernel or a memory copy on "
"the stream, and you are done."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:184
msgid "Running the recipe: four ways to execute"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:186
msgid ""
"Once you have a `DeviceOperation`, you need to trigger it. cuda-oxide gives "
"you four paths, ranging from \"do everything for me\" to \"I'll handle it "
"myself.\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:189
msgid "`.sync()` -- block and wait"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:191
msgid ""
"The simplest option. The scheduling policy picks a stream, runs the "
"operation, and blocks the calling thread until the stream is idle:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:194
msgid "let result: Vec<f32> = d2h_operation.sync()?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:198
msgid ""
"This is perfect for scripts, tests, and any place where you just want the "
"answer now. No Tokio runtime needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:201
msgid "`.await` -- yield and resume"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:203
msgid ""
"Inside an async runtime, `.await` does the same thing but without blocking "
"the thread. It converts the operation into a `DeviceFuture`, submits the GPU "
"work, and yields the current task. When the GPU finishes, it wakes the task "
"and delivers the result:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:208
msgid ""
"#[tokio::main]\n"
"async fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {\n"
"    init_device_contexts(0, 1)?;\n"
"\n"
"    let module = kernels::load_async(0)?;\n"
"    // SAFETY: this is 1D, buffers contain 1024 elements, and module/"
"scheduler\n"
"    // both use device 0's context.\n"
"    unsafe {\n"
"        module.vecadd_async(\n"
"            LaunchConfig::for_num_elems(1024),\n"
"            &a_dev,\n"
"            &b_dev,\n"
"            &mut c_dev,\n"
"        )\n"
"    }?\n"
"    .await?;\n"
"\n"
"    Ok(())\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:230
msgid ""
"While the GPU is working, the Tokio runtime is free to poll other tasks -- "
"no thread sits idle waiting for hardware. This is the key to running "
"multiple GPU pipelines concurrently, which we explore in [Concurrent "
"Execution](concurrent-execution.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:235
msgid "`.sync_on(&stream)` -- you choose the stream"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:237
msgid ""
"When you need a specific stream -- for interop with an existing CUDA "
"library, or to guarantee ordering with other work on that stream -- "
"`sync_on` lets you supply it directly and blocks until it completes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:241
msgid ""
"let stream = ctx.new_stream()?;\n"
"operation.sync_on(&stream)?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:246
msgid "`unsafe async_on(&stream)` -- fire and forget"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:248
msgid ""
"The most manual option. It submits work to a stream and returns immediately, "
"**without** synchronizing. The caller must ensure the stream is synchronized "
"before reading results. This is useful for batching many operations onto a "
"stream before a single sync at the end:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:253
msgid ""
"let stream = ctx.new_stream()?;\n"
"unsafe { op_a.async_on(&stream)? };\n"
"unsafe { op_b.async_on(&stream)? };\n"
"stream.synchronize()?;  // now both are done\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:260
msgid "Lifting host data with `value()`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:262
msgid ""
"Not every step in a pipeline involves the GPU. Sometimes you need to feed a "
"host-side value -- a configuration parameter, a set of dimensions, a pre-"
"loaded weight vector -- into a chain of device operations. The `value()` "
"function wraps any `Send` type in a no-op `DeviceOperation` that returns it "
"immediately:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:267
msgid ""
"use cuda_async::device_operation::value;\n"
"\n"
"let weights = vec![1.0f32; 1024];\n"
"let op = value(weights);  // impl DeviceOperation<Output = Vec<f32>>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:274
msgid ""
"On its own, `value()` looks pointless. Its power shows up in composition. If "
"you are zipping together a host-to-device transfer and a configuration "
"struct, `value()` makes the configuration fit the pipeline:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:278
msgid ""
"let (device_buf, config) = zip!(\n"
"    h2d(raw_data),\n"
"    value(ModelConfig { dim: 64, layers: 3 })\n"
").sync()?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:285
msgid ""
"Both arms of `zip!` must be `DeviceOperation`s. `value()` is the adapter "
"that makes host data play nicely with device work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:288
msgid "Talking to the stream with `with_context`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:290
msgid ""
"Some operations need access to the stream itself at execution time. Memory "
"allocation (`malloc_async`), asynchronous copies (`memcpy_htod_async`), and "
"event recording all require a raw `CUstream` handle. But remember -- a "
"`DeviceOperation` does not know which stream it will run on when it is "
"created. The stream is assigned later, by the scheduling policy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:296
msgid ""
"`with_context` bridges this gap. It creates an operation whose body is "
"deferred until the `ExecutionContext` is available:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:299
msgid ""
"use cuda_async::device_operation::{with_context, value};\n"
"use cuda_core::memory::{malloc_async, memcpy_htod_async};\n"
"\n"
"fn h2d(host_data: Vec<f32>) -> impl DeviceOperation<Output = "
"DeviceBox<[f32]>> {\n"
"    with_context(move |ctx| {\n"
"        let stream = ctx.get_cuda_stream();\n"
"        let n = host_data.len();\n"
"        let num_bytes = n * std::mem::size_of::<f32>();\n"
"        unsafe {\n"
"            let dptr = malloc_async(stream.cu_stream(), num_bytes)."
"unwrap();\n"
"            memcpy_htod_async(dptr, host_data.as_ptr(), num_bytes, stream."
"cu_stream())\n"
"                .unwrap();\n"
"            value(DeviceBox::from_raw_parts(dptr, n, ctx.get_device_id()))\n"
"        }\n"
"    })\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:318
msgid ""
"The closure receives the `ExecutionContext` and must return another "
"`DeviceOperation`. Here it returns a `Value` wrapping the freshly allocated "
"device pointer. The inner operation is executed immediately on the same "
"stream."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:322
msgid ""
"This pattern -- `with_context` wrapping raw driver calls, returning "
"`value()` at the end -- is how you turn any low-level CUDA operation into a "
"composable building block. The `async_mlp` example uses it for `h2d`, `d2h`, "
"and `zeros` helpers that slot cleanly into `and_then` chains."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:328
msgid ""
"`with_context` is the escape hatch for raw driver calls that need a "
"`CUstream`. For kernel launches, prefer contracted generated async methods: "
"they handle argument marshalling and buffer lifetimes, and accept a checked "
"`PreparedLaunch<K>`. Uncontracted generated methods still require an unsafe "
"raw-launch proof."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:335
msgid "How the GPU tells Rust it is done"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:337
msgid ""
"When you `.await` a `DeviceOperation`, something interesting happens under "
"the hood. The operation becomes a `DeviceFuture` -- a type that implements "
"Rust's `std::future::Future` -- and the async runtime polls it. But how does "
"a poll- based system know when *hardware* has finished its work?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:342
msgid ""
"The answer is `cuLaunchHostFunc`, a CUDA driver API that enqueues a host-"
"side callback into a stream. When all preceding GPU work on that stream "
"finishes, the driver calls the callback on a driver thread. cuda-oxide uses "
"this to build a zero-busy-wait bridge between CUDA and Rust's async model."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:347
msgid "The `DeviceFuture` is a three-state machine:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:349
msgid ""
"  Idle ───poll()───► Executing ───callback fires───► Complete\n"
"                         │                               │\n"
"                   (submit GPU work               (return result\n"
"                    + enqueue callback)             to the runtime)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:356
msgid "On the **first poll**, the future:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:358
msgid "Calls `execute()` on the operation, submitting GPU work to the stream."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:359
msgid ""
"Enqueues a `cuLaunchHostFunc` callback on the **same stream**, right after "
"the GPU work. CUDA guarantees stream ordering: this callback will not fire "
"until the kernel finishes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:362
msgid "Returns `Poll::Pending`. The async runtime parks the task and moves on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:364
msgid ""
"When the **GPU finishes** the kernel, the CUDA driver calls the host "
"callback on a driver thread. The callback sets an `AtomicBool` flag and "
"wakes the task's `AtomicWaker`. The async runtime notices the wake and re-"
"polls the future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:369
msgid ""
"On the **second poll**, the future sees the flag and returns `Poll::"
"Ready(Ok(result))`. The task resumes with the value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:372
msgid ""
"The critical property: **no host thread spins or sleeps** while the GPU "
"works. The async executor is free to run other tasks -- including other "
"`DeviceFuture`s on other streams. This is how cuda-oxide achieves true "
"concurrent execution without dedicating a thread per GPU operation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/the-device-operation-model.md:378
msgid ""
"The [Combinators and Composition](combinators-and-composition.md) chapter "
"shows how to build multi-stage pipelines from these primitives, and "
"[Scheduling and Streams](scheduling-and-streams.md) explains how the "
"scheduling policy selects a stream and creates the `ExecutionContext` that "
"ties everything together."
msgstr ""
